We recommend that the Municipal Accountant:
Send confirmation letters to the national government agencies with downloaded funds to LGU-Caibiran to determine actual amount of unliquidated fund transfers;
Trace and review the transactions affecting each Payable account in the books of LGU-Caibiran to determine its validity;
support each account with a schedule containing vital information such as date of transfer or age of the payable; and
maintain a subsidiary ledger for each fund transfer and make periodic reconciliation of balances with the Municipal Treasurer.
We also recommend that the Municipal Treasurer:
review the transactions in the bank accounts for Trust Fund;
tally and reconcile the balances with records of the Municipal Accountant; and
return all funds due to the national government that had not been utilized for two years or more to avoid idle funds and misuse by the LGU in coordination with the Municipal Agriculture Service Officer and other LGU officials concerned.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:
conduct an inspection and inventory of all lots for rent of the Municipality;
prepare a master list of all Municipal lots for rent with the names of the lessees, location and area of each lot.;
draft the Contract of Lease for each lessee, specifying all necessary provisions for compliance by both parties;
submit the Contract of Lease to the Municipal Mayor, duly signed by the lessees, together with the master list;
enforce payment of  all rents on the dates and rates specified in the Lease Contracts.
We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor convene its Local Finance Committee and require them to review the current Revenue Code of the Municipality, verify if rental of lots were included therein and recommend revisions to update the rates and fees, for submission to the Sangguniang Bayan.
The LGU management did not submit their reply to this audit observation.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
pay the mandated daily minimum wage of Job Order personnel as prescribed by the RTWPB for Region VIII and consider reduction of the number of JOs in the LGU to those which are considered essential and urgent;
revise the Contract of Service of Job Order personnel to include information on their specific duties, assigned areas, rates, period covered by the contract, address, pictures and signed as acknowledgement by the JO being hired;
require all JOs, prior to payment of wages, to submit an accomplishment report, duly filled-up and validated by the LGU official who is the JO’s immediate supervisory;
compel the Accountant and Treasurer to pay JO wages only when the payroll is duly supported with Contracts (initial payment) and Accomplishment Reports signed by Heads of Offices where they are assigned; and
direct the Municipal Accountant to use the correct expense account code in recording payments of  wages of Job Order personnel with the Chart of Accounts for LGUs as his guide and as mandated by his profession.
Management believes that Section 4 of the Wage Order No. VIII 20 & 21 applies only to all minimum wage earners in the PRIVATE SECTOR in the Region, and that the employer, if there is employer-employee relation at all, is a local government unit not a private entity. Hence, it cannot be compelled to follow the said order. Management also cited that even CSC, COA and DILG Joint Circular No. 1,s.2017 as amended by Joint Circular No. 1, s. 2018 entitled “Rules and Regulations Governing Contracts of Service and Job Order Workers in the Government”, itself didn’t impose upon local governmet units the minimum wage rate or any applicable rate to its job order personnel.  Furthermore, Section 76 of the Local Government Code on Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern. provides that: “Every Local Government Unit shall design and implement its own organizational structure and staffing pattern, taking into consideration its service requirements and financial capability, subject to the minimum standards and guidelines prescribed by the Civil Service Commission”.   This consequently gives autonomy and independence to local government units in hiring personnel.
Contrary to the assertion of the LGU, the RTWPB Wage Order No. VIII 20 & 21 is applicable to persons hired as Job Orders by the LGU.  Since there is no employer-employee relationship between the JO and the LGU, the JOs are not considered government employees, thus, they belong to the private sector covered by Labor Laws of the Philippines.  And It is the regulations of the RTWPB that regulates their wages as the DBM regulates the salaries of government employees.
If taken and interpreted in the proper context, Section 76 of RA No. 7160 that governs the Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern of LGUs,  LGU-Caibiran should have by this time a duly approved plantilla as its own organizational structure and staffing pattern, which in the course of its preparation, have taken into consideration the requirements of the different offices and the financial capability of the LGU, such that, there would be no need for the LGU to hire additional Job Order personnel. If there is indeed a need for additional workers, the LGU has to limit the number of JOs to be hired in order to comply with the minimum wage requirement.
Lastly, the autonomy and independence of LGU-Caibiran is not absolute as it is bound by laws being enforced by the Philippine government and its agencies.

